The In- dians use snuff as a medicine, stuffing it into their 6315, when they find them badly affected by the rain or wind. The jugglers vauntingly affirm, that they have it in their power to per- form cures by words alone. Sitting on the sick man’s bed they sing extemporary verses, as magical charnis, either to reconcile the evil spirit, or to call up the shades of the dead by whose assistance they hope to remove all dis- eases. But away with this superstitious non- sense.
